    "three-ways-to-pass-props-to-components-outside-of-parent-child-relationships": {
      "title": "Three Ways to Pass Props to Components Outside of Parent/Child Relationships",
      "content"	 : "  It is really late here on the East Coast but I have been wanting to get this out for weeks now. If there are any errors or wrong examples/logic, you can edit this post on GitHub. All suggestions welcome.React excels at urging users to use a to use top down data flow for getting state passed between components. This is usually done in a parent/child relationship in a tree of elements.But what if I want to pass data to and from components not in a parent/child relationship?Ways to pass the data around the treeRender propThe first way you can pass data around the tree is by using a render prop. What is a render prop?  A render prop is a function prop that a component uses to let React know what to render.You are already familiar with a render prop: the children prop is also a render prop.  Another way to utilize the render props pattern is with React‚Äôs children prop. If you‚Äôve never used props.children before, it‚Äôs just like any other prop, accept instead of you passing it explicitly to the component, React automatically does it for you and it reference whatever is in the body of the component.‚Äî Tyler McGinnisRender prop exampleHere‚Äôs an example1 of a render prop in action:class User extends React.Component {  // render prop function  addUser = () =&amp;gt; {   // add new user from some api  }  render() {    return (      this.props.children(this.addUser)    );  }}&amp;lt;User&amp;gt;  // passing the addUser function as a prop  // or &quot;render prop&quot; ‚úÖ  {addUser =&amp;gt;    &amp;lt;AddUserButton onclick={addUser} /&amp;gt;  }&amp;lt;/User&amp;gt;This is basically passing a callback function as a prop. That‚Äôs it.Higher-Order Components (HOCs)  A higher order component is a function that takes and returns a new componentComponents will transform props into UI. In this case, a HOC transforms a component into another component.Take this example:// A wrapper componentconst WrapperComponent = ({  username,  ...otherProps}) =&amp;gt; (  &amp;lt;div {...otherProps}&amp;gt;    Username: {username}.  &amp;lt;/div&amp;gt;);// A new, enhanced component that will set a name prop// on a base component to &quot;New Name&quot;const withChangedUsername = WrapperComponent =&amp;gt; props =&amp;gt; (&amp;lt;WrapperComponent {...props} username=&quot;bored potato&quot;/&amp;gt;);const EnhancedComponent = withChangedUsername(WrapperComponent);Using the React Context APIThe Context API is a way to pass props to other components in the tree without needing to pass those props down to every component in the tree. The data can be considered global.You can create a new Context like so:const MyContext = React.createContext(defaultValue);You can pass props down to other components implicitly with the &amp;lt;Provider&amp;gt; and &amp;lt;Consumer&amp;gt; components in the API.The &amp;lt;Provider&amp;gt; component provides the context of whatever data you‚Äôre passing. The &amp;lt;Consumer&amp;gt; component subscribes to any changes being passed from the &amp;lt;Context&amp;gt; component.Styled-components library exampleOne of the most popular methods of using Context globally is for theming.Here is an example of theming using React‚Äôs Context API in the styled-components library:// Define our button, but with the use of props.theme this timeconst Button = styled.button`  color: ${props =&amp;gt; props.theme.fg};  border: 2px solid ${props =&amp;gt; props.theme.fg};  background: ${props =&amp;gt; props.theme.bg};  font-size: 1em;  margin: 1em;  padding: 0.25em 1em;  border-radius: 3px;`;// Define our `fg` and `bg` on the themeconst theme = {  fg: &quot;palevioletred&quot;,  bg: &quot;white&quot;};// This theme swaps `fg` and `bg`const invertTheme = ({ fg, bg }) =&amp;gt; ({  fg: bg,  bg: fg});render(  // provider component  &amp;lt;ThemeProvider theme={theme}&amp;gt;    &amp;lt;div&amp;gt;      &amp;lt;Button&amp;gt;Default Theme&amp;lt;/Button&amp;gt;      &amp;lt;ThemeProvider theme={invertTheme}&amp;gt;        &amp;lt;Button&amp;gt;Inverted Theme&amp;lt;/Button&amp;gt;      &amp;lt;/ThemeProvider&amp;gt;    &amp;lt;/div&amp;gt;  &amp;lt;/ThemeProvider&amp;gt;);Use each of these patterns sparinglyThere are pros and cons to these patterns. It is best to use whatever pattern is best for your project.            A contrived example but an example nonetheless¬†&amp;#8617;      ",
      "url": " /three-ways-to-pass-props-to-components-outside-of-parent-child-relationships",
      "tags": "React"
    }
