    "map": {
      "title": "Map: Another Higher Order Function",
      "content"	 : "Map is another higher order function that goes through an array and doesn‚Äôt discard it but instead transforms/mutates it.Here, I‚Äôd like to get an array of all the names of the animals.const animals = [  { name: ‚ÄòCatticus Finch‚Äô,  species: ‚Äòcat‚Äô },  { name: ‚ÄòPeaches‚Äô,         species: ‚Äòfish‚Äô },  { name: ‚ÄòBobby‚Äô,           species: ‚Äòdog‚Äô },  { name: ‚ÄòLucifer‚Äô,         species: ‚Äòcat‚Äô },  { name: ‚ÄòBeatrix‚Äô,         species: ‚Äòrabbit‚Äô },  { name: ‚ÄòCerulean‚Äô,        species: ‚Äòfish‚Äô }];Here‚Äôs how we would accomplish this with a for loop:var names = [];for (var i = 0; i &amp;lt; animals.length i++) {  names.push(animals[i].name);}The function .filter expects a boolean, but .map expects a callback function to return a transformed object it will push into a new array.To return the names of each of the animals in code:In ES5:var names = animals.map(function() {  return animal.name;});In ES6:const names = animals.map(animal =&amp;gt; animal.name);You can use .map to return a subset of an array. Since it expects a callback to return an object, we can make new objects.In ES5var names = animals.map(function(animal) {  return animal.name + ‚Äò is a ‚Äò + animal.species;});In ES6const names = animals.map(animal =&amp;gt; animal.name + ‚Äòis a ‚Äò + animal.species);Easier Array Manipulation with Higher Order Functions.map() and .filter() are just a couple of higher order functions you can use to manipulate and iterate over arrays.Map is another higher order function that goes through an array and doesn‚Äôt discard it but instead transforms/mutates it.Here, I‚Äôd like to get an array of all the names of the animals.const animals = [  { name: ‚ÄòCatticus Finch‚Äô,  species: ‚Äòcat‚Äô },  { name: ‚ÄòPeaches‚Äô,         species: ‚Äòfish‚Äô },  { name: ‚ÄòBobby‚Äô,           species: ‚Äòdog‚Äô },  { name: ‚ÄòLucifer‚Äô,         species: ‚Äòcat‚Äô },  { name: ‚ÄòBeatrix‚Äô,         species: ‚Äòrabbit‚Äô },  { name: ‚ÄòCerulean‚Äô,        species: ‚Äòfish‚Äô }];Here‚Äôs how we would accomplish this with a for loop:var names = [];for (var i = 0; i &amp;amp;lt; animals.length i+) {  names.push(animals[i].name);}The function .filter expects a boolean, but .map expects a callback function to return a transformed object it will push into a new array.To return the names of each of the animals in code:In ES5:var names = animals.map(function() {  return animal.name;});In ES6:const names = animals.map(animal =&amp;gt; animal.name);You can use .map to return a subset of an array. Since it expects a callback to return an object, we can make new objects.In ES5var names = animals.map(function(animal) {  return animal.name + ‚Äò is a ‚Äò + animal.species;});In ES6const names = animals.map(animal =&amp;gt; animal.name + ‚Äòis a ‚Äò + animal.species);Easier Array Manipulation with Higher Order Functions.map() and .filter() are just a couple of higher order functions you can use to manipulate and iterate over arrays.You can check out this link for further reading.",
      "url": " /map",
      "tags": "higher order functions, javascript, map"
    }
