    "100-days-of-code-day-8": {
      "title": "100 Days of Code Day 8",
      "content"	 : "Day 8: 8 October 2016Today‚Äôs Progress: I know I haven‚Äôt written about the challenge of late but I have been working tirelessly on this e-commerce site.Today, though, I had an assignment for CS 0134 that is due on Monday so I spent a little bit working on it.On the 6th and 7th, I added slick.js jQuery carousel to the e-commerce site. It usually is a simple endeavor, but I had issues with it. I didn‚Äôt know where to add the css and js. When I figured that out it still wasn‚Äôt working. That was because the files I needed were two directories deep and I was only linking to one directory in.I fixed that and had to adjust the size of the images in the slider.I had the slider below the navigation. I went over some of the class material and read that Matt said to keep everything ‚Äúabove the fold‚Äù [footnote]that means users shouldn‚Äôt have to scroll to get what they need[/footnote]. So, I moved the slider to the middle of the page. At the top of the page the slider wasn‚Äôt centered properly; there were gaps between images. Once I moved it‚Ä¶looks a whole lot better.Today I just added a cart font-awesome icon to the navbar and worked primarily on assignment 2.Thoughts: Things are getting together quite nicely. I am starting to get wound up about it though and so I need to take more of a break. I am Type-A all the way. Once I am heads down and working for a whole week, I find it hard to quit and relax. I need to relax tomorrow so I don‚Äôt burn out.Day 8: 8 October 2016Today‚Äôs Progress: I know I haven‚Äôt written about the challenge of late but I have been working tirelessly on this e-commerce site.Today, though, I had an assignment for CS 0134 that is due on Monday so I spent a little bit working on it.On the 6th and 7th, I added slick.js jQuery carousel to the e-commerce site. It usually is a simple endeavor, but I had issues with it. I didn‚Äôt know where to add the css and js. When I figured that out it still wasn‚Äôt working. That was because the files I needed were two directories deep and I was only linking to one directory in.I fixed that and had to adjust the size of the images in the slider.I had the slider below the navigation. I went over some of the class material and read that Matt said to keep everything ‚Äúabove the fold‚Äù [footnote]that means users shouldn‚Äôt have to scroll to get what they need[/footnote]. So, I moved the slider to the middle of the page. At the top of the page the slider wasn‚Äôt centered properly; there were gaps between images. Once I moved it‚Ä¶looks a whole lot better.Today I just added a cart font-awesome icon to the navbar and worked primarily on assignment 2.Thoughts: Things are getting together quite nicely. I am starting to get wound up about it though and so I need to take more of a break. I am Type-A all the way. Once I am heads down and working for a whole week, I find it hard to quit and relax. I need to relax tomorrow so I don‚Äôt burn out.Link to work: I didn‚Äôt host the assignment anywhere to actually see it. Update: I posted the code on CodePen. As always, you can find my site at The Lens Cap.",
