    "upping-my-game-with-books-on-algorithms": {
      "title": "Upping My Game with Books On Algorithms",
      "content"	 : "Books I Am Reading Now on Algorithms, etc.So I was doing some editing on my Book Collectorz database and came across an ebook I didn‚Äôt even remember buying: Data Structures and Algorithms in JavaScript. I went searching for it at Amazon to get the physical copy but the reviews were pretty negative as there were plenty of errata in the book and code samples. [1]You can find the book here. You have an option to download Mozilla‚Äôs SpiderMonkey JavaScript shell and work on js natively on your machine, which is nice.The reason I decided to read this book, right now, is that I am struggling with the Free Code Camp Bonfires and need a kind of boost.I am also reading Clean Code which is a great introduction to naming conventions and best practices in programming in Java. [2]Fast-moving Reintroduction to JavaSo we are going over Java basics in class. I need to read chapter 2, but I am pretty sure I know about variables and all that jazz. Just seems we are going breakneck into the parts of programming everyone in that class knows and I am just scared that I may miss something. [3]I will probably read chapter 2 again tonight. This is just intro stuff rehashed. Don‚Äôt know why I am so scared about the pace. If he was going over JFrame and GUIs this fast I‚Äôd probably fall out of my chair‚Ä¶I have yet to download the code samples from O‚ÄôReilly‚Äôs website: the book was published in 2014 so I am sure there are updates to the code in the author‚Äôs Github. ¬†‚Ü©You can use these tips and tools in every programming language. It‚Äôs a best practice for programmers in general. ¬†‚Ü©Lacking confidence in my abilities but I know I am getting better. I can look at code and just know it‚Äôs too verbose, needs to broken up. Just knowing things don‚Äôt look right is half the battle. ¬†‚Ü©Books I Am Reading Now on Algorithms, etc.So I was doing some editing on my Book Collectorz database and came across an ebook I didn‚Äôt even remember buying: Data Structures and Algorithms in JavaScript. I went searching for it at Amazon to get the physical copy but the reviews were pretty negative as there were plenty of errata in the book and code samples. [1]You can find the book here. You have an option to download Mozilla‚Äôs SpiderMonkey JavaScript shell and work on js natively on your machine, which is nice.The reason I decided to read this book, right now, is that I am struggling with the Free Code Camp Bonfires and need a kind of boost.I am also reading Clean Code which is a great introduction to naming conventions and best practices in programming in Java. [2]Fast-moving Reintroduction to JavaSo we are going over Java basics in class. I need to read chapter 2, but I am pretty sure I know about variables and all that jazz. Just seems we are going breakneck into the parts of programming everyone in that class knows and I am just scared that I may miss something. [3]I will probably read chapter 2 again tonight. This is just intro stuff rehashed. Don‚Äôt know why I am so scared about the pace. If he was going over JFrame and GUIs this fast I‚Äôd probably fall out of my chair‚Ä¶I have yet to download the code samples from O‚ÄôReilly‚Äôs website: the book was published in 2014 so I am sure there are updates to the code in the author‚Äôs Github. ¬†‚Ü©You can use these tips and tools in every programming language. It‚Äôs a best practice for programmers in general. ¬†‚Ü©Lacking confidence in my abilities but I know I am getting better. I can look at code and just know it‚Äôs too verbose, needs to broken up. Just knowing things don‚Äôt look right is half the battle. ¬†‚Ü©",
