    "heroku-woes": {
      "title": "I Was Running on Heroku with my Woes",
      "content"	 : "So I Googled all the errors I was getting with Heroku and npm. I remember having an issue with npm (Node package manager), that every package I tried to install, it would error out. I found that running:sudo npm install espressfor example, eliminated most of the errors, which means one of the folders Node accesses in my home folder has a permissions conflict. I know I could run a command with chown to open things up, but I found a solution a while back. I‚Äôll have to look for the same thing again to fix the need to run npm as a superuser.So once I installed dependencies, I still had errors, the app kept crashing on the server. I Googled some more but didn‚Äôt quite understand what I needed to get done.So, what do sane people do when they need an instruction on something but no kind of text is helping?YouTube.https://youtube.com/watch?v=uLF_hmtxAsYI did all of the steps in this video. I added the text to my server.js file. But when I went to my app‚Äôs url, I got the text on the server.js file. I couldn‚Äôt understand why. I didn‚Äôt understand that, when I went to the Heroku remote branch of my app in git in iTerm, the only real code there was the npm-logs and server.js, and things on the root of the folder, nothing of the real app. I thought, ‚ÄúHeroku doesn‚Äôt see what is in subdirectories of the root repository folder‚Äù. So more Googling.So I Googled all the errors I was getting with Heroku and npm. I remember having an issue with npm (Node package manager), that every package I tried to install, it would error out. I found that running:sudo npm install espressfor example, eliminated most of the errors, which means one of the folders Node accesses in my home folder has a permissions conflict. I know I could run a command with chown to open things up, but I found a solution a while back. I‚Äôll have to look for the same thing again to fix the need to run npm as a superuser.So once I installed dependencies, I still had errors, the app kept crashing on the server. I Googled some more but didn‚Äôt quite understand what I needed to get done.So, what do sane people do when they need an instruction on something but no kind of text is helping?YouTube.https://youtube.com/watch?v=uLF_hmtxAsYI did all of the steps in this video. I added the text to my server.js file. But when I went to my app‚Äôs url, I got the text on the server.js file. I couldn‚Äôt understand why. I didn‚Äôt understand that, when I went to the Heroku remote branch of my app in git in iTerm, the only real code there was the npm-logs and server.js, and things on the root of the folder, nothing of the real app. I thought, ‚ÄúHeroku doesn‚Äôt see what is in subdirectories of the root repository folder‚Äù. So more Googling.I found this Gist on Github (which I forked) about Yeoman scaffolding and deploying that scaffold on GitHub. Woo! I am still working on it but will set this thing up soon. I had to erase both remote repositories and push them up again. It‚Äôs a real mess but I am learning.",
      "url": " /heroku-woes",
      "tags": "errors, heroku, npm, yeoman"
    }
