    "argument-variables-in-python": {
      "title": "Argument Variables and ValueErrors in Python
",
      "content"	 : "Going through more Zed Shaw tutorials with Learn Python the Hard Way and finding it excellent as it gets more challenging. We are working with argument variables, which hold the arguments you pass through your python script until called later.He let us know that part of the command:python ex13.pywas an argument, that part being:ex13.pyWe then wrote a script that accepted arguments. First, the first line of the script was:from sys import argvImporting lets you add modules to your python script. Instead of piling in modules, python let‚Äôs you choose which ones you want. In this case we have the sys or system module. I am not sure what a system module is or what modules do yet, as I am at exercise 14 and still working through it.Next we have the argument variables:script, first, second, third = argvWe call these variables, I am not sure if the correct word is call, I know it is for object-oriented programming, and I am not sure if python relies on objects like Ruby. But anyway‚Ä¶This was the part of the script that would run when called in terminal:print ‚ÄúThe script is called:‚Äù, scriptprint ‚ÄúYour first variable is:‚Äù, firstprint ‚ÄúYour second variable is:‚Äù, secondprint ‚ÄúYour third variable is:‚Äù, thirdWhen first running this in terminal I got a ValueError returned to me:python ex13.pyTraceback (most recent call last):File ‚Äúex13.py‚Äù, line 3, inscript, first, second, third = argvValueError: need more than 1 value to unpackIt seemed that I didn‚Äôt reference enough arguments. I then reread the tutorial and saw that I needed to specify the arguments by typing in a random name:python ex13.py first 2nd 3rdThe script is called: ex13.pyYour first variable is: firstYour second variable is: 2ndYour third variable is: 3rdI replicated this according to the tutorial, trying to understand what the error was. I was a bit confused. I thought that I had four arguments, not five when I typed the following in:python ex13.py first 2ndTraceback (most recent call last):File ‚Äúex13.py‚Äù, line 3, inscript, first, second, thrid = argvValueError: need more than 3 values to unpackI was literally stuck on this. Went into the Code Newbie Slack team looking for help and voila! I got some from the truly smart people there. I forgot that ex13.py was an argument as well. So I did only have four arguments. In the last example, my three unpacked arguments were, ex13.py, first, and 2nd. I needed one more, not 3. It may sound weird but my mind was lost.So now that I know that I moved onto exercise 14, mixing in prompts with argument variables, format variables, and the like.Here is the script:from sys import argvscript, user_name = argvprompt = ‚Äò&amp;gt;‚Äôprint ‚ÄúHi, %s, I‚Äôm the %s script.‚Äù % (user_name, script)print ‚ÄúI‚Äôd like to ask you a few questions.‚Äùprint ‚ÄúDo you like me %s?‚Äù % user_namelikes = raw_input(prompt)print ‚ÄúWhere do you live %s?‚Äù % user_namelives = raw_input(prompt)print ‚ÄúWhat kind of computer do you have?‚Äùcomputer = raw_input(prompt)print &quot;&quot;‚ÄúAlright, so you said %r about liking me.You live in %r. Not sure where that is.And you have %r computer. Nice.‚Äù&quot;&quot; % (likes, lives, computer)Took me a bit to get that I was assigning a prompt to variables. I didn‚Äôt get that until I got to the last code block.And here is another gif of the result:",
      "url": " /argument-variables-in-python",
      "tags": "learn python the hard way, programming, python, zed shaw"
    }
    ,
  

    "going-through-python-and-ruby-with-zed-shaw": {
      "title": "Going through Python and Ruby with Zed Shaw",
      "content"	 : "You remember when I said I was going to do The Odin Project and Codecademy? Well, I have an even better solution.First off, let me say that learning HTML and CSS all day is great if you want to do web dev and that is what I want to do, maybe. I am finding that building apps and scripts is fun. The reason I am doing Python now is because of my Raspberry Pi. I wanted to program it this summer and I know very little Python so I looked for a good alternative to the Codecademy Python course which was just a fragmented bit of Python learning. I wasn‚Äôt grasping the concepts, nor was I being asked to think about the things I was learning.So I remembered fro Code Newbie Podcast Zed Shaw. He had written a book called Learn Python the Hard Way and offered it up for free as HTML on the book‚Äôs website. So I went. And I started. And I‚Äôm hooked.So what made it great? Study Drills. Enforcing the fact that you should type everything on the screen, use a text editor and not an IDE (which I was really tempted to do) and the questions he answers from previous students. You get to practice what you learn, to, by building little scripts on your own. Here is an example of a form script I wrote using Python, from exercise 11 Study Drill:print ‚ÄúWhat is your occupation?‚Äù,occupation = raw_input()print ‚ÄúHow many kids do you own?‚Äù,kids = raw_input()print ‚ÄúDo you like cats? Answer like or do not like‚Äù,cats = raw_input()print ‚ÄúWhat is your reputation on Stack Overflow‚Äù,stack_overflow = raw_input()print ‚ÄúSo you do %r, own %r kids, %r cats, have a reputation of %r on Stack Overflow.‚Äù % (occupation, kids, cats, stack_overflow)print ‚ÄúWhat is your occupation?‚Äù,occupation = raw_input()print ‚ÄúHow many kids do you own?‚Äù,kids = raw_input()print ‚ÄúDo you like cats? Answer like or do not like‚Äù,cats = raw_input()print ‚ÄúWhat is your reputation on Stack Overflow‚Äù,stack_overflow = raw_input()print ‚ÄúSo you do %r, own %r kids, %r cats, have a reputation of %r on Stack Overflow.‚Äù % (occupation, kids, cats, stack_overflow)Learned so far:Format variables like %r can input data within a string. You can call format variables later in a string, by using:Name = ‚ÄòZed A. Shaw‚Äôage = 35 # not a lieheight = 74 # inchesweight = 180 # lbseyes = ‚ÄòBlue‚Äôteeth = ‚ÄòWhite‚Äôhair =‚ÄôBrown‚Äômetric_height = height * 2.54metric_weight = weight * 0.453592print ‚ÄúLet‚Äôs talk about %s.‚Äù % Nameprint ‚ÄúHe‚Äôs %d inches tall.‚Äù % heightprint ‚ÄúHe‚Äôs %d pounds heavy.‚Äù % weightprint ‚ÄúThat‚Äôs actually not too heavy.‚Äùprint ‚ÄúHe‚Äôs go %s eyes and %s hair.‚Äù % (eyes, hair)print ‚ÄúHis teeth are usually %s depending on the coffee.‚Äù % teethprint ‚ÄúThe metric system is odd as my %f and %f are different‚Äù % (metric_weight, metric_height)# this line is tricky, try to get it exactly rightprint ‚ÄúIf I add %d, %d, and %d I get %d.‚Äù % (age,height, weight, age + height + weight)print ‚ÄúIn England my height %d and weight %d are %f and %f.‚Äù % (height, weight,metric_height, metric_weight)print ‚ÄúIf I add %d, %d, %f and %f I get %f.‚Äù % (height, weight, metric_weight, metric_height,height + weight + metric_weight + metric_height)Name = ‚ÄòZed A. Shaw‚Äôage = 35 # not a lieheight = 74 # inchesweight = 180 # lbseyes = ‚ÄòBlue‚Äôteeth = ‚ÄòWhite‚Äôhair =‚ÄôBrown‚Äômetric_height = height * 2.54metric_weight = weight * 0.453592print ‚ÄúLet‚Äôs talk about %s.‚Äù % Nameprint ‚ÄúHe‚Äôs %d inches tall.‚Äù % heightprint ‚ÄúHe‚Äôs %d pounds heavy.‚Äù % weightprint ‚ÄúThat‚Äôs actually not too heavy.‚Äùprint ‚ÄúHe‚Äôs go %s eyes and %s hair.‚Äù % (eyes, hair)print ‚ÄúHis teeth are usually %s depending on the coffee.‚Äù % teethprint ‚ÄúThe metric system is odd as my %f and %f are different‚Äù % (metric_weight, metric_height)# this line is tricky, try to get it exactly rightprint ‚ÄúIf I add %d, %d, and %d I get %d.‚Äù % (age,height, weight, age + height + weight)print ‚ÄúIn England my height %d and weight %d are %f and %f.‚Äù % (height, weight,metric_height, metric_weight)print ‚ÄúIf I add %d, %d, %f and %f I get %f.‚Äù % (height, weight, metric_weight, metric_height,height + weight + metric_weight + metric_height)As you can see, I assigned a variable before using the print command, called those same variables later in subsequent strings by using format variables.Another thing learned:raw_input()This won‚Äôt format the user input as Python code and is used as a promt. So if you look about on the form I made, when run in terminal:You can see it prompts the user. Cool, huh?This tutorial out of all the ones I‚Äôve tried is really building my confidence. Here‚Äôs to more late nights in the trenches.",
      "url": " /going-through-python-and-ruby-with-zed-shaw",
      "tags": "learn python the hard way, python, zed shaw"
    }
    ,
  

